{"title_page": "Sarangarh State", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \u0938\u093e\u0930\u0902\u0917\u0922\u093c \u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0938\u0924\n|conventional_long_name = Sarangarh State\n|common_name = Sarangarh\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = 91\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 = \n|flag_s1    = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Sarangarh.png\n|image_coat = \n|image_map  = Sakti-Raigarh-Imperial Gazetteer.jpg\n|image_map_caption = Sarangarh State in the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India]]\n|stat_area1 = 1399\n|stat_year1 = 1901 \n|stat_pop1  = 79,900 \n|footnotes  =\n}}\n'''Sarangarh''' was a [[princely state]] in [[India]] during the [[British Raj]] ruled by a [[Gonds|Raj Gond dynasty]].<ref>Great Britain India Office. ''Imperial Gazetteer of India,'' Volume 21. 1909</ref> The emblem of the state was a [[turtle]].\n\nIts capital was in [[Sarangarh]] town, now in [[Chhattisgarh]] state. \nThe state had no significant towns except for its capital. Its area was 1,399 square km with a population of 79,900 persons according to the 1901 census.\n\n==History==\nAccording to legend Sarangarh state was founded in the first century AD by [[Gondi people|Gond]] ancestors that had migrated from [[Bhandara]]. It was originally a dependency of the [[Ratanpur Kingdom]] and later became one of the eighteen [[Garhjat]] states under [[Sambalpur State]]<ref>[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/s/sarangarh.html Sarangarh Princely State]</ref> The Sambalpur kings favoured Sarangarh owing to its readiness to help their kingdom during military campaigns.<ref>Great Britain India Office. ''Imperial Gazetteer of India,'' Volume 21. 1909</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Sarangarh became a [[British protectorate]]. Between 1878 and 1889 Sarangarh state was placed under the direct administration of British India owing to economic mismanagement and the infancy of the ruler Bhawani Pratap Singh.<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html Princely States of India]</ref> Sarangarh was a small feudatory state, part of the Chhattisgarh division.<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Chhattisgarh |volume=6 |page=116}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 January 1948 Sarangarh State acceded to the [[Dominion of India|Indian Union]].\n\n===Rulers===\nSarangarh State was one of several [[princely states]] governed by the Raj Gond Dynasty of [[Gondi people|Gonds]]. The rulers bore the title '[[Raja]]'<ref>[http://www.indianrajputs.com/view/sarangarh Rajput Provinces of India \u2013 Sarangarh (Princely State)]</ref>\n\n====Rajas====\n*.... \u2013 ....                Udibhan Singh \n*.... \u2013 ....                Birbhan Singbh \n*.... \u2013 1736                Udho Sai Singh \n*1736 \u2013 1777                Kalyan Sai \n*1777 \u2013 1808                Vishvanath Sai \n*1808 \u2013 1815                Subhadra Sai \n*1827 \u2013  5 January 1828         Bhikhan Sai                        (d. 1828) \n* 5 January 1828 \u2013 1828         Tikan Sai \n*1828 \u2013 May 1829            Gajraj Singh                       (d. 1829)\n*May 1829 \u2013 1872            Singram Singh \n*1872 \u2013 Sep 1889            Bhawani Pratap Singh               (b. c.1865 \u2013 d. 1889) \n*Sep 1889 \u2013  5 August 1890     Lal Raghubir Singh                 (d. 1890) \n* 5 August 1890 \u2013 11 January 1946  Bahadur Jawahir Singh              (b. 1886 \u2013 d. 1946) \n*11 Jan 1946 \u2013 15 August 1947  Naresh Chandra Singh               (b. 1908 \u2013 d. 1987)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Eastern States Agency]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|21.6|N|83.08|E|region:IN-GU_type:city_source:kolossus-cawiki|display=title}}\n{{Princely states of the Eastern States Agency}}\n\n[[Category:Princely states of India]]\n[[Category:History of Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:Raigarh district]]\n[[Category:Rajputs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \u0938\u093e\u0930\u0902\u0917\u0922\u093c \u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0938\u0924\n|conventional_long_name = Sarangarh State\n|common_name = Sarangarh\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = 91\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 = \n|flag_s1    = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Sarangarh.png\n|image_coat = \n|image_map  = Sakti-Raigarh-Imperial Gazetteer.jpg\n|image_map_caption = Sarangarh State in the [[Imperial Gazetteer of India]]\n|stat_area1 = 1399\n|stat_year1 = 1901 \n|stat_pop1  = 79,900 \n|footnotes  =\n}}\n'''Sarangarh''' was a [[princely state]] in [[India]] during the [[British Raj]] ruled by a [[Gonds|Raj Gond dynasty]].<ref>Great Britain India Office. ''Imperial Gazetteer of India,'' Volume 21. 1909</ref> The emblem of the state was a [[turtle]].\n\nIts capital was in [[Sarangarh]] town, now in [[Chhattisgarh]] state. \nThe state had no significant towns except for its capital. Its area was 1,399 square km with a population of 79,900 persons according to the 1901 census.\n\n==History==\nAccording to legend Sarangarh state was founded in the first century AD by [[Gondi people|Gond]] ancestors that had migrated from [[Bhandara]]. It was originally a dependency of the [[Ratanpur Kingdom]] and later became one of the eighteen [[Garhjat]] states under [[Sambalpur State]]<ref>[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/s/sarangarh.html Sarangarh Princely State]</ref> The Sambalpur kings favoured Sarangarh owing to its readiness to help their kingdom during military campaigns.<ref>Great Britain India Office. ''Imperial Gazetteer of India,'' Volume 21. 1909</ref>\n\nIn 1818 Sarangarh became a [[British protectorate]]. Between 1878 and 1889 Sarangarh state was placed under the direct administration of British India owing to economic mismanagement and the infancy of the ruler Bhawani Pratap Singh.<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html Princely States of India]</ref> Sarangarh was a small feudatory state, part of the Chhattisgarh division.<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Chhattisgarh |volume=6 |page=116}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 January 1948 Sarangarh State acceded to the [[Indian Union]].\n\n===Rulers===\nSarangarh State was one of several [[princely states]] governed by the Raj Gond Dynasty of [[Gondi people|Gonds]]. The rulers bore the title '[[Raja]]'<ref>[http://www.indianrajputs.com/view/sarangarh Rajput Provinces of India - Sarangarh (Princely State)]</ref>\n\n====Rajas====\n*.... - ....                Udibhan Singh \n*.... - ....                Birbhan Singbh \n*.... - 1736                Udho Sai Singh \n*1736 - 1777                Kalyan Sai \n*1777 - 1808                Vishvanath Sai \n*1808 - 1815                Subhadra Sai \n*1827 -  5 Jan 1828         Bhikhan Sai                        (d. 1828) \n* 5 Jan 1828 - 1828         Tikan Sai \n*1828 - May 1829            Gajraj Singh                       (d. 1829)\n*May 1829 - 1872            Singram Singh \n*1872 - Sep 1889            Bhawani Pratap Singh               (b. c.1865 - d. 1889) \n*Sep 1889 -  5 Aug 1890     Lal Raghubir Singh                 (d. 1890) \n* 5 Aug 1890 \u2013 11 Jan 1946  Bahadur Jawahir Singh              (b. 1886 - d. 1946) \n*11 Jan 1946 \u2013 15 Aug 1947  Naresh Chandra Singh               (b. 1908 - d. 1987)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Eastern States Agency]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Coord|21.6|N|83.08|E|region:IN-GU_type:city_source:kolossus-cawiki|display=title}}\n{{Princely states of the Eastern States Agency}}\n\n[[Category:Princely states of India]]\n[[Catego